\section*{Graphical Abstract}

Temperate plants are at risk of being exposed to late spring freezes---often called false springs---, which are one of the strongest factors determining temperate plants species range limits and can impose high ecological and economic damage. More studies aimed at understanding relationships among species tolerance and avoidance strategies, climatic regimes, and the environmental cues that underlie spring phenology would improve predictions at all biological levels. An integrated approach to assessing past and future spring freeze damage would provide novel insights into fundamental plant biology, and offer more robust predictions as climate change progresses.

